{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517636"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12817"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.1,0.78,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77462"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5260"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62974"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6629"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35742"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77462"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a one hour history of severe and constant generalised abdominal pain. His history includes a myocardial infarction one year ago and is currently taking aspirin, rosuvastatin and perindopril. On examination his blood pressure is 108/71 mmHg, pulse 115/min, respiratory rate 19/min and temperature: 37.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His abdomen is moderately distended and non tender, and his pain appears to be out of proportion as compared to his examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate imaging modality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duplex ultrasonography","Abdominal X-ray","CT angiography","Catheter angiography","Magnetic resonance imaging angiography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with out-of-proportion abdominal pain of acute onset and this is most likely due to an acute ischaemic event. Bearing in mind his cardiovascular history, this patient probably has mesenteric ischaemia. The initial management plan will be focussed on confirming this diagnosis and identifying the probable site of obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography \u003C/strong\u003Eis the recommended imaging modality for the diagnosis of visceral ischaemic syndromes because it has very high accuracy rates (95-100%) and is a rapid imaging modality that can locate the extent of possible stenosis or occlusion and help in planning revascularisation. This means of imaging can also help in visualising other abdominal structures and ruling out other causes of these signs and symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplex ultrasonography \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be a very useful tool for the diagnosis of visceral vessel diseases, but it would not be appropriate in this scenario because of its high degree of operator dependability, the amount of time required for study and the pressure used for performing ultrasonography. Along with that, it is also difficult to obtain reliable results in patients with obesity, bowel gas, and heavy calcification in the vessels, thus, making it not an ideal investigation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-ray \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be a reasonable initial imaging modality to rule out other pathologies and in this scenario, it can show the \u0027thumb printing\u0027 sign of mural oedema, but this is not specific for mesenteric ischaemia and because the primary pathology is vascular in nature, it is better to go for a CT angiogram.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatheter angiography \u003C/strong\u003Ewas previously used as a standard method for the diagnosis of mesenteric ischaemia, but due to its invasiveness, it is now used as a treatment option after the planning for revascularisation is done. It can also be used for confirming the diagnosis before going for major procedures such as open abdominal exploration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging angiography \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a preferred option in the acute setting due to the amount of time that is required for performing this investigation, along with that it also lacks the necessary resolution and can sometimes lead to overestimating the degree of stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Computed tomography angiography is the imaging modality of choice in patients with suspected acute bowel ischaemia.","Mesenteric ischaemia should be suspected in patients with severe abdominal pain that is disproportionate to physical examination findings, especially in those with a history of cardiovascular disease."],"references":["Clair DG, Beach JM. Mesenteric Ischemia. N Engl J Med. 2016 Mar 10;374(10):959-68. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1503884. PMID: 26962730.","Bala M, Catena F, Kashuk J, De Simone B, Gomes CA, Weber D, Sartelli M, Coccolini F, Kluger Y, Abu-Zidan FM, Picetti E, Ansaloni L, Augustin G, Biffl WL, Ceresoli M, Chiara O, Chiarugi M, Coimbra R, Cui Y, Damaskos D, Di Saverio S, Galante JM, Khokha V, Kirkpatrick AW, Inaba K, Lepp\u00e4niemi A, Litvin A, Peitzman AB, Shelat VG, Sugrue M, Tolonen M, Rizoli S, Sall I, Beka SG, Di Carlo I, Ten Broek R, Mircea C, Tebala G, Pisano M, van Goor H, Maier RV, Jeekel H, Civil I, Hecker A, Tan E, Soreide K, Lee MJ, Wani I, Bonavina L, Malangoni MA, Koike K, Velmahos GC, Fraga GP, Fette A, de\u0027Angelis N, Balogh ZJ, Scalea TM, Sganga G, Kelly MD, Khan J, Stahel PF, Moore EE. Acute mesenteric ischemia: updated guidelines of the World Society of Emergency Surgery. World J Emerg Surg. 2022 Oct 19;17(1):54. doi: 10.1186/s13017-022-00443-x. PMID: 36261857; PMCID: PMC9580452.","Cudnik MT, Darbha S, Jones J, Macedo J, Stockton SW, Hiestand BC. The diagnosis of acute mesenteric ischemia: A systematic review and meta-analysis. Acad Emerg Med. 2013 Nov;20(11):1087-100. doi: 10.1111/acem.12254. PMID: 24238311."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62974"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62974"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T08:32:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T17:50:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5260"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77462"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"